12562559,Managing outpatient asthma exacerbations.,Roy SR||Milgrom H,"Roy, Sitesh R||Milgrom, Henry",Curr Allergy Asthma Rep. 2003 Mar;3(2):179-89. doi: 10.1007/s11882-003-0032-7.,Current allergy and asthma reports,1529-7322 (Print) 1529-7322 (Linking),United States,"Asthma is a chronic inflammatory disease that renders individuals prone to acute exacerbations. Several allergic and nonallergic triggers can incite an asthma exacerbation. The goals of managing an asthma exacerbation are prompt recognition, rapid reversal of airflow obstruction, prevention of relapses, and forestalling future episodes. A written asthma home-management plan is essential to minimize the severity of exacerbations. Short-acting b-agonists, oxygen, and corticosteroids are fundamental to early intervention in acute asthma exacerbation. Anticholinergics and magnesium sulfate can help nonresponders. Newer agents such as levalbuterol and long-acting b-agonists might be future additions to our armamentarium of drugs to treat acute exacerbations. Initiation or intensification of long-term controller therapy, treatment of co-morbid conditions, and avoidance of possible triggers along with prompt follow-up can help prevent relapses. Listening to patient preferences and concerns to enhance adherence and regular follow-up care can help prevent future episodes.",Journal Article||Review,53.0,10.1007/s11882-003-0032-7 [doi],NLM,15297322
